    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a potent offensive outlook led by **Yordan Alvarez** (80.29) and **Christian Yelich** (75.84). **Yordan Alvarez** remains our premier start, capitalizing on an favorable 4.76 xERA matchup against Emerson Hancock, with his high-tier xwOBA and the #2 lineup slot acting as significant force multipliers. **Junior Caminero** (73.34) also ranks among our elite plays; despite a neutral park factor, his high-upside matchup against the volatile Luis Gil (5.74 xERA) and the protection provided by the #4 spot make him a primary engine for our RBI and HR projections. Meanwhile, **Colt Keith** (68.51) benefits from the best combination of environment and order, with his leadoff assignment against the hittable Chris Paddack providing a strong floor for R and AVG contributions.\n\nStrategic emphasis on speed remains a focal point, though the optimizer favored high-floor starters over pure SB specialists. **Hyeseong Kim** (61.59) secured a spot in the starting nine largely due to his matchup against Kumar Rocker, where the combination of a slow delivery to the plate and favorable wind conditions offers a high probability for a swipe. The most difficult bench decision involved **Josh Smith**, whose score of 52.06 narrowly missed the cut. While **Josh Smith** gained significant utility from his platoon advantage and stolen base potential against a slow-moving Tyler Glasnow, **Caleb Durbin** (56.28) ultimately claimed the final MI spot due to a slightly higher aggregate efficiency score against Dustin May. \n\nOwners should note that all projections are contingent on final lineup confirmations, as every player listed currently rests in a \"Lineup Pending\" status. While **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (66.10) shows strong platoon equity, the 5% wind-in warning at his venue warrants close monitoring, as it could dampen his power ceiling against Carmen Mlodzinski. We are also keeping a close eye on **Dillon Dingler** (48.96); his status is the most precarious, and if he drops lower in the order than our assumed #6, his efficiency could dip below our preferred floor. Proceed with these configurations, but stay alert for late-breaking lineup changes that could force a pivot to **Chase Meidroth** or **Carson Benge**.",
